00:02:16.870 --> 00:02:20.300
Now talking about electric
and magnetic forces,

00:02:20.300 --> 00:02:22.110
you may think it's
a trick question,

00:02:22.110 --> 00:02:24.920
but it's rather subtle.

00:02:24.920 --> 00:02:31.520
All optical forces were derived
from the electric dipole

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:35.650
Hamiltonian D dot
E. This is what

00:02:35.650 --> 00:02:38.790
we used as a starting
point for light forces.

00:02:38.790 --> 00:02:42.890
So my question is, what
about the Lorentz force?

00:02:42.890 --> 00:02:45.840
The Lorentz force comes
from the magnetic part

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:48.100
of the electromagnetic field.

00:02:48.100 --> 00:02:51.690
Now, is there Lorentz
force on the atoms?

00:02:51.690 --> 00:02:55.380
And, if yes, does it contribute
to the light forces or is

00:02:55.380 --> 00:02:56.610
it negligibly small?

00:03:00.190 --> 00:03:02.030
Actually, the question
I'm asking you,

00:03:02.030 --> 00:03:04.630
I don't think it's
addressed in any textbook

00:03:04.630 --> 00:03:06.390
and I think you can
go to conferences

00:03:06.390 --> 00:03:08.450
and ask some of your colleagues.

00:03:08.450 --> 00:03:11.920
You may get a wide
range of answers.

00:03:11.920 --> 00:03:14.790
So but anyway, has anybody
of you thought about it?

00:03:14.790 --> 00:03:18.240
What about, is there Lorentz
force on neutral atoms?

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:19.670
If no, you're done.

00:03:19.670 --> 00:03:23.100
If yes, does it contribute,
is it negligible,

00:03:23.100 --> 00:03:24.270
or is it even dominant?

00:03:30.186 --> 00:03:32.651
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
temperature

00:03:32.651 --> 00:03:35.609
or is equivalent to
the T minus A picture,

00:03:35.609 --> 00:03:39.553
and the T minus A picture
has the Lorentz force, so

00:03:39.553 --> 00:03:41.525
[INAUDIBLE].

00:03:41.525 --> 00:03:42.540
So.

00:03:42.540 --> 00:03:45.320
PROFESSOR: So it
should be included

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:48.520
because we are talking about
two different representations.

00:03:48.520 --> 00:03:50.585
Collin?

00:03:50.585 --> 00:03:51.210
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:03:54.050 --> 00:03:58.070
PROFESSOR: OK, so yes.

00:03:58.070 --> 00:04:00.080
The Lorentz force is included.

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:02.400
Also, when you ride
on D dot E, you

00:04:02.400 --> 00:04:05.880
think it's the electric
force of an electric dipole.

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:07.300
We come to that in a moment.

00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:09.900
The next question is,
do you have any idea

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:13.195
if the Lorentz
force is important

00:04:13.195 --> 00:04:14.320
or whether it's negligible?

00:04:17.442 --> 00:04:19.089
AUDIENCE: For neutral, or?

00:04:19.089 --> 00:04:20.362
PROFESSOR: For neutral atoms.

00:04:25.322 --> 00:04:27.802
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:04:27.802 --> 00:04:32.930
PROFESSOR: OK, who of you is
working on optical lattices

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:36.160
or wants to work on
optical lattices?

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:38.390
OK, just to catch
your attention,

00:04:38.390 --> 00:04:41.390
when the atom goes up and down
the optical lattice, if feels

00:04:41.390 --> 00:04:43.080
the lattice potential.

00:04:43.080 --> 00:04:46.350
The force is 100%
the Lorentz force.

00:04:46.350 --> 00:04:50.400
There is no contribution
from the electric force.

00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:52.200
So that's what I
want to show you now.

00:04:55.200 --> 00:05:02.850
So we have two fundamental
forces, the electric force

00:05:02.850 --> 00:05:07.700
and-- if you have two charges
separated in the field,

00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:10.960
two different electric fields--
we derive from the Coulomb

00:05:10.960 --> 00:05:12.780
force, the dipole force.

00:05:12.780 --> 00:05:15.580
And the force on
the electric dipole

00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:19.255
is-- that potential is-- D
dot E. The gradient of it

00:05:19.255 --> 00:05:25.080
is D times gradient E-- with
correct Victorian notation--

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:29.170
whereas the Lorentz
force is V cross B.

00:05:29.170 --> 00:05:31.458
So these are the two
forces we have to consider.

00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:42.350
Let me show two configurations
where we use dipole forces,

00:05:42.350 --> 00:05:44.230
the stimulated light force.

00:05:44.230 --> 00:05:47.820
One is here where we
focus a laser beam,

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:52.690
and let's just assume for
the sake of the discussion

00:05:52.690 --> 00:05:57.030
that the laser beam--
it's propagating here

00:05:57.030 --> 00:06:00.390
and the linear polarization
goes up and down.

00:06:00.390 --> 00:06:03.320
So now we have a dipole
moment of the atom, which

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:09.210
oscillates up and down, which is
parallel to the electric field.

00:06:09.210 --> 00:06:15.330
So now we have D dot E, and
indeed if you take the atom

00:06:15.330 --> 00:06:19.640
and move it into
the laser beam, it

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:22.020
will experience an
attractive force

00:06:22.020 --> 00:06:24.680
and this attractive
force is purely electric.

00:06:27.300 --> 00:06:30.790
But let's now come to the
situation which many of you

00:06:30.790 --> 00:06:34.820
work on in the laboratory, would
that we have two plane waves--

00:06:34.820 --> 00:06:37.070
so the laser beams are
infinity extended--

00:06:37.070 --> 00:06:41.940
we have two plane waves and
they form an optical lattice.

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:48.450
Now, the dipole, the oscillating
dipole, the electric dipole,

00:06:48.450 --> 00:06:51.090
is again driven by
linearly polarized light.

00:06:51.090 --> 00:06:56.940
It points up, but the
gradient of the electric field

00:06:56.940 --> 00:07:00.680
is in the direction of the
interference of the lattice,

00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:03.010
so the gradient of
the electric field

00:07:03.010 --> 00:07:06.650
is perpendicular to
the dipole moment.

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:11.520
So therefore, D
dot E is exactly 0,

00:07:11.520 --> 00:07:15.310
and therefore, the electric part
of the potential-- the Coulomb

00:07:15.310 --> 00:07:18.470
force which is
microscopically behind it--

00:07:18.470 --> 00:07:21.220
will not contribute anything.

00:07:21.220 --> 00:07:24.720
So I could stop here
and say, well, OK,

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:27.200
since we have only the Coulomb
force and the Lorentz force,

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:29.240
I've proven to you it's
not the Coulomb force,

00:07:29.240 --> 00:07:31.820
so therefore it's
a Lorentz force.

00:07:31.820 --> 00:07:33.220
But let me just tell you why.

00:07:36.560 --> 00:07:42.060
So what I'm really telling you
is it is actually remarkable

00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:45.980
that if you go along
the Z direction

00:07:45.980 --> 00:07:50.560
and we take the Z derivative of
the AC Stock's shift potential,

00:07:50.560 --> 00:07:53.370
and the AC Stock's shift
potential is one half,

00:07:53.370 --> 00:07:55.290
alpha is now the
polarizability--

00:07:55.290 --> 00:07:58.370
we use alpha in many
places-- times E square.

00:07:58.370 --> 00:08:00.590
So this is the AC
Stock's shift potential,

00:08:00.590 --> 00:08:03.490
and the spatial derivative of
the AC Stock's shift potential

00:08:03.490 --> 00:08:06.510
is a force, but it's
the Lorentz force.

00:08:06.510 --> 00:08:07.550
Actually, I was amazed.

00:08:07.550 --> 00:08:09.425
I had to work it out
myself because I haven't

00:08:09.425 --> 00:08:11.900
seen it discussed anywhere,
but you can simply

00:08:11.900 --> 00:08:14.520
take the electric field
of a standing wave,

00:08:14.520 --> 00:08:16.820
perform this derivative,
and what you find

00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:19.010
is you get the Lorentz force.

00:08:19.010 --> 00:08:24.390
If you wonder how you get
it without going through all

00:08:24.390 --> 00:08:29.370
the Victorian notation,
the Lorentz force

00:08:29.370 --> 00:08:34.110
is V cross B. The
velocity of the charge

00:08:34.110 --> 00:08:36.520
is related to the derivative
of the dipole moment.

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:39.720
The dipole moment is
charge times position,

00:08:39.720 --> 00:08:41.380
and the derivative
of the dipole moment

00:08:41.380 --> 00:08:43.570
is charge times velocity.

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:45.750
So don't let yourself
fool yourself.

00:08:45.750 --> 00:08:49.640
When you have an
oscillating field,

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:53.650
there are charges which move
their currents inside the atom.

00:08:53.650 --> 00:08:57.290
So our V cross B, the
V is pretty much D dot.

00:08:57.290 --> 00:09:00.520
The D dot is
polarizability times E dot,

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:03.220
this is alpha
polarizability-- frequency

00:09:03.220 --> 00:09:05.590
times the electric field.

00:09:05.590 --> 00:09:11.170
But, as Cody said, we can
go form P dot A to D dot E--

00:09:11.170 --> 00:09:15.670
or, to be precise-- the magnetic
field is the curl of the vector

00:09:15.670 --> 00:09:20.590
potential, and the curl
gives us the [INAUDIBLE]--

00:09:20.590 --> 00:09:23.520
I'm suppressing Victorian
notation, here--

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:27.570
and you know that E,
the electric field,

00:09:27.570 --> 00:09:32.710
is the temporal derivative of
A, so therefore we get that.

00:09:32.710 --> 00:09:39.260
So if you now multiply D
dot with the curl of A,

00:09:39.260 --> 00:09:42.850
you get something which
is K alpha E square.

00:09:42.850 --> 00:09:47.220
K is for a standing wave,
the spatial derivative.

00:09:47.220 --> 00:09:48.720
So I've shown you--
at least you can

00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:51.160
see by dimensional analysis,
or by just pointing

00:09:51.160 --> 00:09:54.820
to the different terms, that if
you take the AC Stock's shift

00:09:54.820 --> 00:09:56.420
potential through
the derivative,

00:09:56.420 --> 00:09:58.711
you get everything which you
have in the Lorentz force.

00:10:02.480 --> 00:10:05.142
It would be a 10 minute,
easy homework assignment,

00:10:05.142 --> 00:10:07.350
but we're running out of
homework assignments-- we're

00:10:07.350 --> 00:10:11.730
at the end of the semester--
to show that, explicitly.

00:10:11.730 --> 00:10:13.600
So it is really
the Lorentz force

00:10:13.600 --> 00:10:15.424
which provides the
trapping potential

00:10:15.424 --> 00:10:16.340
in an optical lattice.

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:21.210
Questions?

00:10:21.210 --> 00:10:21.710
[INAUDIBLE]

00:10:21.710 --> 00:10:23.336
AUDIENCE: So in
the simple picture

00:10:23.336 --> 00:10:26.108
you have [INAUDIBLE]
the lattice,

00:10:26.108 --> 00:10:29.826
you're saying that the
transverse confinement is

00:10:29.826 --> 00:10:32.526
provided by the
electric force, but what

00:10:32.526 --> 00:10:34.245
about the perpendicular
direction?

00:10:34.245 --> 00:10:37.620
[INAUDIBLE] electric field like
this, but the other direction?

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:40.120
PROFESSOR: OK, I can discuss
with you two simple geometries.

00:10:40.120 --> 00:10:42.310
In one case, in
one direction it's

00:10:42.310 --> 00:10:44.500
the pure Coulomb force at work.

00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:47.010
In the other direction,
it's the pure Lorentz force.

00:10:47.010 --> 00:10:50.670
But in general, when you go
through an AC Stock's shift

00:10:50.670 --> 00:10:52.880
potential, you have both.

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:55.720
So you may wonder that
the Coulomb force, when

00:10:55.720 --> 00:10:58.240
you integrate it, would
not be integrable.

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:00.620
It does not give
rise to potential.

00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:03.740
Also, the Lorentz force does
not give rise to potential.

00:11:03.740 --> 00:11:06.800
But if you add the Coulomb
force and the Lorentz force,

00:11:06.800 --> 00:11:11.750
you can integrate it up to
the optical dipole potential.

00:11:11.750 --> 00:11:15.060
I find it remarkable,
but it is what it is.

00:11:23.105 --> 00:11:23.605
Questions?

00:11:26.230 --> 00:11:30.490
So energy conservation, yes.

00:11:30.490 --> 00:11:32.490
That's a good thing
to discuss now.

00:11:38.170 --> 00:11:42.450
Let me first discuss I want
to have-- energy conservation

00:11:42.450 --> 00:11:47.270
has to be discussed with
two different perspectives.

00:11:47.270 --> 00:11:49.797
One is a transient
phenomenon-- which

00:11:49.797 --> 00:11:52.380
I'll do in a few minutes-- but
let me first discuss something,

00:11:52.380 --> 00:11:56.270
which is CW, and this
is the following.

00:11:56.270 --> 00:12:00.690
You have atoms which move
over a standing wave,

00:12:00.690 --> 00:12:04.220
and I use the dressed
atom picture to show you

00:12:04.220 --> 00:12:07.880
that-- for a strong, blue
detuned standing wave--

00:12:07.880 --> 00:12:09.830
we have a friction force.

00:12:09.830 --> 00:12:12.790
So the atom-- this was
the Sisyphus cooling--

00:12:12.790 --> 00:12:17.360
that the atom is climbing up
hills, there's some transition,

00:12:17.360 --> 00:12:19.650
climbs up the next hill,
but on average the atom

00:12:19.650 --> 00:12:23.390
climbs up more hills
than it scoots down,

00:12:23.390 --> 00:12:25.485
and therefore
there is work done.

00:12:25.485 --> 00:12:30.150
There is a net force, and this
net force provides friction.

00:12:30.150 --> 00:12:33.090
It slows down the
velocity of the atom.

00:12:33.090 --> 00:12:37.280
My question to you is,
where has this energy gone?

00:12:37.280 --> 00:12:41.200
The kinetic energy lost by atom,
where does this energy appear?

00:12:48.570 --> 00:12:49.471
Which fields?

00:12:49.471 --> 00:12:52.700
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
the laser beam?

00:12:52.700 --> 00:12:56.580
PROFESSOR: Well, we have two
fields, the laser fields,

00:12:56.580 --> 00:13:01.440
and we have maybe a
spontaneous emission?

00:13:01.440 --> 00:13:05.940
But the force is only a
stimulated force due to-- yeah?

00:13:09.970 --> 00:13:11.618
Which fields?

00:13:11.618 --> 00:13:13.100
AUDIENCE: The laser field?

00:13:13.100 --> 00:13:16.064
Because when you stimulate
into a laser field,

00:13:16.064 --> 00:13:20.030
your [INAUDIBLE]
modulator [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:20.030 --> 00:13:24.470
PROFESSOR: Well, I have a
little bit problem with that

00:13:24.470 --> 00:13:27.530
because when the
atoms-- the force

00:13:27.530 --> 00:13:30.190
comes from distributing
photons from one standing

00:13:30.190 --> 00:13:33.900
wave to the other one, and these
are photons of equal frequency.

00:13:36.510 --> 00:13:44.230
So in that sense, the net effect
is that those two laser beams--

00:13:44.230 --> 00:13:45.880
actually, the atom moves, here.

00:13:45.880 --> 00:13:48.840
So what should happen
to the laser beams?

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:52.930
Photons are not disappearing.

00:13:59.872 --> 00:14:02.330
I will later tell you, in the
transient picture-- and this,

00:14:02.330 --> 00:14:04.913
maybe you've already done your
homework assignment number 10--

00:14:04.913 --> 00:14:06.970
there is something
happening to the laser beam.

00:14:06.970 --> 00:14:09.905
But this would only
happen when atoms fly in

00:14:09.905 --> 00:14:12.030
and fly out of a laser beam.

00:14:12.030 --> 00:14:14.060
Then we have a
different situation.

00:14:14.060 --> 00:14:18.120
But here, if the atoms stay in
the laser beam the laser beam--

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:22.050
so to speak-- sees a constant
index of refraction medium.

00:14:22.050 --> 00:14:24.500
It just goes through
and nothing has

00:14:24.500 --> 00:14:28.630
happened to the photons except
that-- occasionally-- photons

00:14:28.630 --> 00:14:30.040
are spontaneously emitted.

00:14:33.760 --> 00:14:34.470
Well, OK.

00:14:34.470 --> 00:14:40.320
If it's not the laser
beams, what remains now?

00:14:43.754 --> 00:14:45.170
AUDIENCE: Spontaneous
[INAUDIBLE].

00:14:45.170 --> 00:14:47.100
PROFESSOR: Spontaneous emission.

00:14:47.100 --> 00:14:55.170
Now how can spontaneous
emission carry the energy?

00:14:57.720 --> 00:14:59.940
What is the spectrum of
spontaneous emission?

00:15:04.740 --> 00:15:05.676
AUDIENCE: Triplets?

00:15:05.676 --> 00:15:07.050
PROFESSOR: Yes,
the mono-triplet.

00:15:07.050 --> 00:15:11.000
We have the central
carrier, the central carrier

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.750
is not carrying away
any energy because it

00:15:13.750 --> 00:15:16.320
is at the laser frequency.

00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:18.420
Now we have two side bands.

00:15:18.420 --> 00:15:21.810
Can the side bands
carry away energy?

00:15:21.810 --> 00:15:23.190
AUDIENCE: Interlacing them.

00:15:23.190 --> 00:15:24.110
PROFESSOR: Huh?

00:15:24.110 --> 00:15:26.410
AUDIENCE: Interlacing
with the [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:26.410 --> 00:15:29.178
PROFESSOR: Asymmetry
in what sense?

00:15:29.178 --> 00:15:32.440
AUDIENCE: If the side bands
are [INAUDIBLE] escape.

00:15:32.440 --> 00:15:35.020
PROFESSOR: Well, but
didn't we discuss,

00:15:35.020 --> 00:15:38.580
with a radiative cascade,
that the blue detuned side

00:15:38.580 --> 00:15:41.060
bend comes when you go from
the upper dressed level

00:15:41.060 --> 00:15:42.870
to the dressed level?

00:15:42.870 --> 00:15:44.710
And in the lower
dressed level, you

00:15:44.710 --> 00:15:48.554
can only emit a red detuned side
band, not a blue detuned side

00:15:48.554 --> 00:15:49.090
bands.

00:15:49.090 --> 00:15:50.960
What we said in the
radiative cascade

00:15:50.960 --> 00:15:55.800
after one blue detuned photon,
there is a red detuned photon.

00:15:55.800 --> 00:15:59.290
So the number of photons
emitted on the red side band

00:15:59.290 --> 00:16:01.530
and on the blue side
band are exactly equal.

00:16:04.470 --> 00:16:04.970
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:16:04.970 --> 00:16:07.630
AUDIENCE: But then you have the
[INAUDIBLE] cooling picture,

00:16:07.630 --> 00:16:11.796
where the red detuned side then
was emitted in the lower field

00:16:11.796 --> 00:16:12.490
region?

00:16:12.490 --> 00:16:13.470
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:16:13.470 --> 00:16:15.530
So the situation
is the following.

00:16:15.530 --> 00:16:17.900
The atom emits an
equal number red, blue.

00:16:17.900 --> 00:16:21.110
Red detuned and blue detuned,
red detuned and blue detuned.

00:16:21.110 --> 00:16:23.125
But when it emits
the blue detuned,

00:16:23.125 --> 00:16:26.210
the side bend spacing
is larger because it

00:16:26.210 --> 00:16:29.490
emits the blue detuned photon
when it's on top of the hill.

00:16:29.490 --> 00:16:32.260
And the red detuned
photon is emitted

00:16:32.260 --> 00:16:34.860
when the atom is
more in the dark,

00:16:34.860 --> 00:16:37.670
and therefore, the side
bend spacing is lower.

00:16:37.670 --> 00:16:40.400
So it alternates
blue, red, blue, red.

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:44.280
But the blue detuned photon is
emitted when the generalized RB

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:47.810
frequency is larger, when
the atoms is at an anti-node

00:16:47.810 --> 00:16:51.300
And the red detuned is
more preferably emitted

00:16:51.300 --> 00:16:58.050
when the photon is at a
node of the standing wave.

00:16:58.050 --> 00:17:01.170
So it is the difference
of these modulations,

00:17:01.170 --> 00:17:04.420
the side bands are modulated,
and there is a preference

00:17:04.420 --> 00:17:06.920
to emit the blue detuned
side band when the side band

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:09.829
spacing is larger than
in the red detuned case.

00:17:09.829 --> 00:17:13.670
And this is where
the energy goes.

00:17:13.670 --> 00:17:15.690
AUDIENCE: You could make
the argument and that

00:17:15.690 --> 00:17:19.396
would give a simple picture
for the maximum cooling rate?

00:17:19.396 --> 00:17:20.020
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:17:20.020 --> 00:17:22.810
AUDIENCE: Where you have omega
times your [? scattering ?]

00:17:22.810 --> 00:17:23.750
rate?

00:17:23.750 --> 00:17:24.520
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:17:24.520 --> 00:17:29.180
That's exactly how, last class,
I calculated the cooling rate.

00:17:29.180 --> 00:17:32.180
The cooling rate, the energy
removed from the system,

00:17:32.180 --> 00:17:46.960
is, well, yeah, I said it is
the height of the lattice,

00:17:46.960 --> 00:17:48.650
but the height of
the lattice is also

00:17:48.650 --> 00:17:53.710
the amount by which
the-- the lattice is

00:17:53.710 --> 00:17:56.230
nothing else than the
generalized RB frequency.

00:17:56.230 --> 00:17:58.860
This is the energy level
of one crest level,

00:17:58.860 --> 00:18:01.760
and therefore the
lattice is the increment

00:18:01.760 --> 00:18:04.090
by which we modulate
blue and red side bands.

00:18:04.090 --> 00:18:06.620
Exactly.

00:18:06.620 --> 00:18:08.870
This can be
quantitatively worked out.

00:18:08.870 --> 00:18:11.620
If I had another half hour,
I could do it for you.

00:18:11.620 --> 00:18:13.480
It's in the
references, but this is

00:18:13.480 --> 00:18:17.990
the physical
picture for cooling.

00:18:17.990 --> 00:18:26.870
OK, but so you realize, this
is one of the subtleties.

00:18:26.870 --> 00:18:29.450
We can understand
the force simply

00:18:29.450 --> 00:18:33.090
from a simple picture, energy
levels, Sisyphus cooling

00:18:33.090 --> 00:18:35.120
and such, but in
order to understand

00:18:35.120 --> 00:18:38.330
where the energy comes from,
we need the mono-triplet.

00:18:38.330 --> 00:18:40.580
We need spontaneous emission.

00:18:40.580 --> 00:18:44.690
So the force comes from the
redistribution of photons.

00:18:44.690 --> 00:18:46.135
It's the stimulated
redistribution

00:18:46.135 --> 00:18:48.600
of photons which is
responsible for the force,

00:18:48.600 --> 00:18:51.940
but the energy
balance comes from,

00:18:51.940 --> 00:18:56.330
what can be neglected for
the momentum balance, namely

00:18:56.330 --> 00:19:00.270
the few spontaneous emission
events, and especially

00:19:00.270 --> 00:19:03.870
those which involve the
blue and red side bands.

00:19:03.870 --> 00:19:05.880
And it beautifully
works together

00:19:05.880 --> 00:19:09.840
and all the equation
of physics are obeyed.

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:14.610
OK, but that tells you now
that the cooling effect

00:19:14.610 --> 00:19:19.440
hinges on spontaneous emission.

00:19:19.440 --> 00:19:21.541
And yes, spontaneous
emission is dissipation.

00:19:21.541 --> 00:19:23.540
And whenever you want the
friction coefficient--

00:19:23.540 --> 00:19:26.300
you want dissipation--
you need an open system

00:19:26.300 --> 00:19:28.550
and the open system is
spontaneous emission

00:19:28.550 --> 00:19:29.870
into those nodes.

00:19:29.870 --> 00:19:32.840
So let's now talk about
an opposite situation

00:19:32.840 --> 00:19:36.290
where we do not have any
spontaneous emission.

00:19:36.290 --> 00:19:38.010
And I think almost
all the people

00:19:38.010 --> 00:19:41.330
who work with optical lattices
use infrared lasers for them,

00:19:41.330 --> 00:19:44.300
or [INAUDIBLE] detuned laser
where spontaneous emission

00:19:44.300 --> 00:19:47.395
happens only once
every 20, 30 seconds

00:19:47.395 --> 00:19:51.410
or 100 seconds per atom, so
we can really neglect it.

00:19:51.410 --> 00:19:53.350
So now the question
is the following.

00:19:53.350 --> 00:19:55.830
Assume you have a
focused laser beam

00:19:55.830 --> 00:19:58.290
and you load a
Bose-Einstein condensate

00:19:58.290 --> 00:20:00.830
at the edge of the cloud,
and now the condensate

00:20:00.830 --> 00:20:05.150
is accelerated, sucked
into the laser beam.

00:20:05.150 --> 00:20:08.550
So now the atom
has kinetic energy.

00:20:08.550 --> 00:20:13.510
The question is, where does
this kinetic energy come from?

00:20:13.510 --> 00:20:16.210
And this time, we do not
have spontaneous emission

00:20:16.210 --> 00:20:19.630
as we have when we do
frictional cooling.

00:20:19.630 --> 00:20:23.140
So the question is now, where
does the energy of the atom

00:20:23.140 --> 00:20:23.640
come from?

00:20:28.520 --> 00:20:31.936
AUDIENCE: But if we were talking
about a dielectric medium,

00:20:31.936 --> 00:20:37.304
it's coming from those light
waves that are reflected or not

00:20:37.304 --> 00:20:39.760
reflected.

00:20:39.760 --> 00:20:42.220
PROFESSOR: If comes
from those light rays,

00:20:42.220 --> 00:20:45.590
but-- the atom is a dielectric
medium, that's good--

00:20:45.590 --> 00:20:52.560
but the reflection and
deflection of light rays--

00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:55.670
at least in leading order-- you
would say photons of the same

00:20:55.670 --> 00:20:57.702
energy are deflected--

00:20:57.702 --> 00:21:01.638
AUDIENCE: Wouldn't the
[INAUDIBLE] of the atom

00:21:01.638 --> 00:21:07.060
just get absorbed [INAUDIBLE]
and the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:21:07.060 --> 00:21:09.540
PROFESSOR: I would hate to
use the picture of absorption

00:21:09.540 --> 00:21:11.090
and emission.

00:21:11.090 --> 00:21:13.610
What really happens is
it's just scattering.

00:21:13.610 --> 00:21:14.740
It's scattering.

00:21:14.740 --> 00:21:17.670
you scatter a photon
which has one frequency

00:21:17.670 --> 00:21:19.017
into a different direction.

00:21:19.017 --> 00:21:20.225
It's really light scattering.

00:21:23.540 --> 00:21:30.056
Well, you have a homework
assignment on that,

00:21:30.056 --> 00:21:32.430
and I don't need to go into
details because it can easily

00:21:32.430 --> 00:21:36.790
be worked out, but what
happens is the following.

00:21:36.790 --> 00:21:39.290
The atom is a dielectric medium.

00:21:39.290 --> 00:21:41.210
It has an index of refraction.

00:21:41.210 --> 00:21:45.050
And if you put an
index-- if you suddenly

00:21:45.050 --> 00:21:48.990
put an index of refraction
into a laser beam--

00:21:48.990 --> 00:21:52.770
then you change the
phase of the laser beam.

00:21:52.770 --> 00:21:56.760
The atoms act as an
electro-optical modulator,

00:21:56.760 --> 00:22:01.600
and they change the frequency
of the transmitted photons.

00:22:01.600 --> 00:22:03.780
You have a homework
assignment on that.

00:22:03.780 --> 00:22:06.580
So if you increase the number
of atoms in your laser beam,

00:22:06.580 --> 00:22:10.540
because they move in,
this is-- the phase

00:22:10.540 --> 00:22:13.960
of the transmitted
photons is shifted.

00:22:13.960 --> 00:22:17.740
If the phase of the photons is
shifted during a certain time,

00:22:17.740 --> 00:22:20.390
phase over time is frequency.

00:22:20.390 --> 00:22:23.630
So therefore you will see,
when the atoms move in and gain

00:22:23.630 --> 00:22:28.880
kinetic energy, the transmitted
photons of the laser beam

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:31.250
have lost some energy.

00:22:31.250 --> 00:22:34.100
They are slightly
shifted to the red.

00:22:34.100 --> 00:22:36.800
So in other words, it's funny
but if you have a dipole trap

00:22:36.800 --> 00:22:39.020
and the laser beam
is focused and atoms

00:22:39.020 --> 00:22:41.750
slosh through the trap,
if you would carefully

00:22:41.750 --> 00:22:44.590
analyze the frequency
of the transmitted beam,

00:22:44.590 --> 00:22:46.890
you will find that it's a
little bit blue, a little bit

00:22:46.890 --> 00:22:48.390
red, a little bit
blue, a little bit

00:22:48.390 --> 00:22:52.130
red, and this compensates
for the kinetic energy.

00:22:52.130 --> 00:22:54.800
Again, I don't think you'll
find it in any textbook.

00:22:54.800 --> 00:22:57.900
It confused me for a while
until I could work it out.

00:22:57.900 --> 00:23:01.280
But the homework assignment
gives you an exact dissoluble

00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:04.060
model where you can exactly
show what I told you.

00:23:07.580 --> 00:23:10.680
So these are the two
situations, here.

00:23:10.680 --> 00:23:12.230
It's either
spontaneous emission,

00:23:12.230 --> 00:23:14.160
which is responsible
for cooling,

00:23:14.160 --> 00:23:17.320
but here we have a
conservative potential.

00:23:17.320 --> 00:23:19.510
And in this
conservative potential,

00:23:19.510 --> 00:23:22.660
the only player is the laser
beam which is transmitted.

00:23:22.660 --> 00:23:27.640
And, indeed, it is the photons
which have been transmitted,

00:23:27.640 --> 00:23:29.850
and usually you wouldn't
put that into your picture.

00:23:29.850 --> 00:23:32.640
Remember, the dipole
force can be explained

00:23:32.640 --> 00:23:35.710
by eliminating the
coherent field of the laser

00:23:35.710 --> 00:23:39.280
field-- for canonical
transformation--

00:23:39.280 --> 00:23:41.000
and then we have a C number.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:42.910
We have a classical
electric field.

00:23:42.910 --> 00:23:46.090
This is your Hamiltonian,
and from this Hamiltonian,

00:23:46.090 --> 00:23:49.610
you derive that you have
a conservative potential.

00:23:49.610 --> 00:23:52.750
But if you now ask
where the energy goes,

00:23:52.750 --> 00:23:54.840
the energy-- really,
in this situation--

00:23:54.840 --> 00:23:58.250
goes into a frequency
shift of the photons.

00:23:58.250 --> 00:24:00.470
Also, in your
Hamiltonian, you have

00:24:00.470 --> 00:24:04.440
assumed that the electric field
is an external classical field,

00:24:04.440 --> 00:24:10.110
E naught times cosine omega T.

00:24:10.110 --> 00:24:13.070
Well, if you want
my advice, whenever

00:24:13.070 --> 00:24:17.130
you use the AC Stock's
shift for trapping,

00:24:17.130 --> 00:24:19.420
just use the AC Stock's
shift and regard it

00:24:19.420 --> 00:24:22.370
as a classic potential,
and just completely forget

00:24:22.370 --> 00:24:25.470
that there are photons behind
because if you want to account

00:24:25.470 --> 00:24:28.310
what really happens to the
photons-- what really happens

00:24:28.310 --> 00:24:31.522
to the energy in this
system-- it really gets ugly

00:24:31.522 --> 00:24:32.855
and it can get really confusing.

00:24:37.586 --> 00:24:38.086
Questions?

00:24:44.528 --> 00:24:48.625
OK, we are done with
the stimulated force.

00:24:48.625 --> 00:24:51.660
We are now in
preparation for next week

00:24:51.660 --> 00:24:54.340
when I want to tell you
about degenerate Fermi gases

00:24:54.340 --> 00:24:57.440
and degenerate Bose gases.

00:24:57.440 --> 00:25:00.920
Those gases require
nanokelvin temperatures,

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:03.840
so today, in the
next hour, I want

00:25:03.840 --> 00:25:05.830
to tell you what
are the techniques

00:25:05.830 --> 00:25:10.000
to create such
ultra-low temperatures,

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:11.860
and the techniques
I want to discuss

00:25:11.860 --> 00:25:14.770
is one addition
to laser cooling.

00:25:14.770 --> 00:25:17.950
We have so far discussed laser
cooling to the Doppler limit,

00:25:17.950 --> 00:25:20.250
but now I have to tell
you that that's not

00:25:20.250 --> 00:25:21.900
where laser cooling stops.

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:26.310
You can go sub-Doppler
and sub-recoil.

00:25:26.310 --> 00:25:29.990
And, at least when
the Nobel Prize

00:25:29.990 --> 00:25:32.610
was given to Bill Phillips,
Steve Chu, and Claude

00:25:32.610 --> 00:25:36.750
Cohen-Tannoudji, well, if
you go to the Nobel website

00:25:36.750 --> 00:25:40.964
and read the report of the
Nobel Committee-- well,

00:25:40.964 --> 00:25:42.630
they should have given
it to those three

00:25:42.630 --> 00:25:44.560
people for the many,
many wonderful things

00:25:44.560 --> 00:25:47.130
they have done, and I've
made frequent references

00:25:47.130 --> 00:25:47.910
to their work.

00:25:47.910 --> 00:25:50.020
Bill Phillips invented
Zeeman slower,

00:25:50.020 --> 00:25:52.760
Claude Cohen-Tannoudji invented
the dressed atom picture,

00:25:52.760 --> 00:25:54.790
they have many,
many contributions,

00:25:54.790 --> 00:25:58.265
but the Nobel Committee
tried to justify their choice

00:25:58.265 --> 00:26:01.240
with a coherent story,
and the coherent story

00:26:01.240 --> 00:26:04.750
was Steve Chu cooled to the
Doppler limit in molasses,

00:26:04.750 --> 00:26:07.700
Bill Phillips discovered
sub-Doppler cooling,

00:26:07.700 --> 00:26:11.600
and Claude Cohen-Tannoudji
realized sub-recoil cooling.

00:26:11.600 --> 00:26:15.005
So the storyline was
cold, colder, the coldest.

00:26:15.005 --> 00:26:16.660
And that's what we
want to talk today.

00:26:19.630 --> 00:26:24.620
So sub-Doppler cooling.

00:26:24.620 --> 00:26:27.770
Well, I could have spent--
or, 10 years ago, I

00:26:27.770 --> 00:26:29.710
spent a whole lecture
on sub-Doppler cooling,

00:26:29.710 --> 00:26:32.210
polarization gradient cooling.

00:26:32.210 --> 00:26:33.150
Wonderful!

00:26:33.150 --> 00:26:38.200
The kind of epiphany of
elegance in [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:38.200 --> 00:26:40.250
a mechanical
description of an atom.

00:26:40.250 --> 00:26:43.130
But I have to say--
and then I explained,

00:26:43.130 --> 00:26:45.380
in another lecture,
sub-recoil cooling,

00:26:45.380 --> 00:26:48.080
how you can even cool
below the recoil limit.

00:26:48.080 --> 00:26:53.200
Well, this year, 2013,
I spent 15 minute on it.

00:26:53.200 --> 00:26:55.920
The reason is the following.

00:26:55.920 --> 00:27:00.420
When I joined atomic
physics and was a post-doc

00:27:00.420 --> 00:27:02.460
in the '90s and
assistant professor,

00:27:02.460 --> 00:27:05.180
the conference's
[INAUDIBLE] of [INAUDIBLE],

00:27:05.180 --> 00:27:09.690
[INAUDIBLE] was full on intents
to find new ways to laser cool.

00:27:09.690 --> 00:27:12.770
Ideas of how to get to lower
and lower temperatures.

00:27:12.770 --> 00:27:16.120
There were many, many
different-- sub-Doppler,

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:18.200
sub-recoil techniques
were discussed.

00:27:18.200 --> 00:27:19.990
This was the main topic.

00:27:19.990 --> 00:27:23.160
But then suddenly,
in 1995, evaporative

00:27:23.160 --> 00:27:26.770
cooling-- an intellectually
boring cooling technique,

00:27:26.770 --> 00:27:29.160
just have atoms
collide and evaporate--

00:27:29.160 --> 00:27:31.770
this led to the lowest
temperature ever,

00:27:31.770 --> 00:27:34.110
and it was almost a
sudden transition.

00:27:34.110 --> 00:27:37.930
Within a few months there was
no research, no papers anymore,

00:27:37.930 --> 00:27:39.940
on advanced methods
of laser cooling.

00:27:39.940 --> 00:27:42.860
Evaporative cooling it
just completely wiped out

00:27:42.860 --> 00:27:45.200
this area over atomic physics.

00:27:45.200 --> 00:27:47.940
The reason being because
all cooling schemes which

00:27:47.940 --> 00:27:51.590
have been discussed had,
in the end, some problems.

00:27:51.590 --> 00:27:53.990
At some point, photons heat.

00:27:53.990 --> 00:27:58.770
Heat because they excite an atom
and if an excited atom collides

00:27:58.770 --> 00:28:01.980
with another atom, there is
a heating mechanism and such.

00:28:01.980 --> 00:28:07.100
So even all the optimistic
proposals for laser cooling

00:28:07.100 --> 00:28:10.930
reached very low temperature,
but never at high density.

00:28:10.930 --> 00:28:14.270
And evaporative cooling
just did everything for you.

00:28:14.270 --> 00:28:18.700
But anyway, I think it-- not
just because a Nobel Prize was

00:28:18.700 --> 00:28:21.760
given for sub-Doppler
and sub-recoil cooling,

00:28:21.760 --> 00:28:24.900
this is really an accomplishment
to understand how can you

00:28:24.900 --> 00:28:27.710
go through conventional
cooling limits,

00:28:27.710 --> 00:28:31.800
and at least every
graduate student

00:28:31.800 --> 00:28:34.280
who happens to graduate
in AMO physics at MIT

00:28:34.280 --> 00:28:36.090
should know what
are the concepts

00:28:36.090 --> 00:28:40.030
behind sub-Doppler and
sub-recoil cooling.

00:28:40.030 --> 00:28:43.110
So what I need in order to
introduce those cooling methods

00:28:43.110 --> 00:28:47.450
for you is I have to remind
you that optical pumping is

00:28:47.450 --> 00:28:52.170
a cooling scheme, and one could
actually say, to some extent,

00:28:52.170 --> 00:28:57.010
every cooling you do with lasers
is based on optical pumping.

00:28:57.010 --> 00:28:58.790
And so let me explain that.

00:28:58.790 --> 00:29:02.200
Optical pumping
happens that-- let's

00:29:02.200 --> 00:29:05.130
say you have a level
structure with a circularly

00:29:05.130 --> 00:29:09.340
polarized light where you can
go maybe from M equals 1 to M

00:29:09.340 --> 00:29:10.540
equals zero.

00:29:10.540 --> 00:29:13.550
And then there can be
spontaneous emission back to M

00:29:13.550 --> 00:29:17.020
equals 1 and back to M equals
minus 1, but the laser--

00:29:17.020 --> 00:29:19.820
because it has
angular momentum--

00:29:19.820 --> 00:29:24.000
cannot excite this state
to any excited state.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:26.220
So what happens is, of
course, pretty clear.

00:29:26.220 --> 00:29:29.530
You have whatever distribution
you have in state one and two.

00:29:29.530 --> 00:29:32.930
You switch on your laser,
and after a few cycles

00:29:32.930 --> 00:29:35.680
everything has fallen
into the dark state.

00:29:35.680 --> 00:29:39.210
You have 100%
population in stage two.

00:29:39.210 --> 00:29:41.910
So this is the simplest
example of optical

00:29:41.910 --> 00:29:45.650
pumping using the
three-level scheme.

00:29:45.650 --> 00:29:49.890
Well, you may ask now, what
has that to do with cooling?

00:29:49.890 --> 00:29:54.400
Well, temperature is
a Boltzmann factor,

00:29:54.400 --> 00:29:58.880
and if you-- we can define
a temperature by saying

00:29:58.880 --> 00:30:04.770
the population
between two levels

00:30:04.770 --> 00:30:07.160
is given by a Boltzmann factor.

00:30:07.160 --> 00:30:10.100
Let's just introduce an
energy-splitting delta

00:30:10.100 --> 00:30:14.340
E-- which is somewhat arbitrary
here-- but in any event,

00:30:14.340 --> 00:30:18.000
you see if you completely
pump out a level,

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:20.810
if you have all the
population in one state,

00:30:20.810 --> 00:30:24.010
this corresponds to
zero temperature.

00:30:24.010 --> 00:30:27.540
So if you optically pump
the atoms, preferentially,

00:30:27.540 --> 00:30:30.710
into certain states,
you have lowered

00:30:30.710 --> 00:30:33.320
the entropy of the system, the
atoms are no longer distributed

00:30:33.320 --> 00:30:35.400
over as many states
as before, and this

00:30:35.400 --> 00:30:38.960
corresponds to
lower temperature.

00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:40.700
And the message I
want to give you

00:30:40.700 --> 00:30:46.360
is that you can understand
laser cooling as optical pumping

00:30:46.360 --> 00:30:49.760
in translation space
in velocity space.

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:53.920
When you laser cool, you excite
the atoms at high velocity

00:30:53.920 --> 00:30:56.590
and then because of the
mechanisms we discussed,

00:30:56.590 --> 00:30:59.860
spontaneous emission
leads to lower velocities,

00:30:59.860 --> 00:31:03.750
and this is one form
of optical pumping.

00:31:03.750 --> 00:31:07.340
I also like the word-- optical
pumping is, in some sense,

00:31:07.340 --> 00:31:09.060
a spontaneous Raman process.

00:31:09.060 --> 00:31:11.360
You go up with one
photon, you go down

00:31:11.360 --> 00:31:13.260
with-- you go up with
the laser photon,

00:31:13.260 --> 00:31:16.390
you go down with the
spontaneously emitted photon.

00:31:16.390 --> 00:31:18.660
So this is a spontaneous
Raman process,

00:31:18.660 --> 00:31:22.790
and laser cooling-- even if
you have just a single ground

00:31:22.790 --> 00:31:26.150
state-- can be regarded
as a Raman process

00:31:26.150 --> 00:31:29.340
where the initial and
final state differ

00:31:29.340 --> 00:31:31.120
in velocity or momentum.

00:31:31.120 --> 00:31:32.900
You have the same
internal state,

00:31:32.900 --> 00:31:34.820
but you have a different
external state.

00:31:34.820 --> 00:31:38.274
So you can see laser cooling
is spontaneous Raman scattering

00:31:38.274 --> 00:31:39.690
between different
momentum states.

00:31:43.110 --> 00:31:54.300
OK, now how can we achieve
sub-Doppler cooling?

00:31:54.300 --> 00:32:02.270
Sub-Doppler cooling
was discovered in 1988,

00:32:02.270 --> 00:32:05.320
and I remember I was at the
[? IKA ?] Conference in Paris

00:32:05.320 --> 00:32:07.800
when Bill Phillips'
group said, we've

00:32:07.800 --> 00:32:09.620
carefully measured
the temperature

00:32:09.620 --> 00:32:11.780
and in sodium we measure
a temperature which

00:32:11.780 --> 00:32:14.930
is lower than the Doppler limit,
which was rigorously derived.

00:32:14.930 --> 00:32:18.510
I derived for you the
Doppler limit of molasses.

00:32:18.510 --> 00:32:20.710
So what went wrong here?

00:32:20.710 --> 00:32:24.160
Well, it became clear
the only loophole--

00:32:24.160 --> 00:32:26.440
if you have a theory
which predicts something

00:32:26.440 --> 00:32:28.770
and then you find a
violation, you carefully

00:32:28.770 --> 00:32:30.510
have to check the assumption.

00:32:30.510 --> 00:32:32.420
And the assumption
which was made--

00:32:32.420 --> 00:32:34.200
and which we have
made in this course--

00:32:34.200 --> 00:32:37.390
is that you had a
two-level system.

00:32:37.390 --> 00:32:41.520
Now, atoms have
hyperfine structure--

00:32:41.520 --> 00:32:43.550
and for pedagogical
reasons, because I

00:32:43.550 --> 00:32:46.070
want to explain to you why
in sub-Doppler cooling scheme

00:32:46.070 --> 00:32:48.590
I assume this hyperfine
structure with F

00:32:48.590 --> 00:32:51.260
equals one half, F
equals three half--

00:32:51.260 --> 00:32:54.340
but let me first tell you
what the novel feature is

00:32:54.340 --> 00:33:02.370
about a multi-level atom
which has hyperfine structure.

00:33:02.370 --> 00:33:06.430
Now, the one thing
which happens is

00:33:06.430 --> 00:33:10.820
that-- instead of just going
between our single ground state

00:33:10.820 --> 00:33:14.950
and our single excited state--
we now have transitions.

00:33:14.950 --> 00:33:17.225
You may want to call
them Raman transitions,

00:33:17.225 --> 00:33:21.070
or optical pumping, between
the hyperfine atoms.

00:33:21.070 --> 00:33:24.900
So there are now transitions
not only up to an excited

00:33:24.900 --> 00:33:27.860
state which rapidly
decays, there

00:33:27.860 --> 00:33:31.270
are now transitions--
Raman transitions--

00:33:31.270 --> 00:33:39.310
between ground states which
have a very low widths.

00:33:39.310 --> 00:33:42.290
The width of the
excited state is gamma.

00:33:42.290 --> 00:33:46.890
Well, what is the width
of the ground state?

00:33:46.890 --> 00:33:49.580
Well, if you don't
have a laser beam,

00:33:49.580 --> 00:33:52.770
the width is zero,
but if you have

00:33:52.770 --> 00:33:56.670
laser beams the atom
doesn't stay there forever.

00:33:56.670 --> 00:34:01.550
There will be a time, which
is estimated here-- depending

00:34:01.550 --> 00:34:04.700
on the RB frequency and the
detuning-- this is the time,

00:34:04.700 --> 00:34:07.150
this is simply nothing
else than the scattering

00:34:07.150 --> 00:34:09.510
rate which we derived before.

00:34:09.510 --> 00:34:13.170
So that's the rate at
which you scatter photons.

00:34:13.170 --> 00:34:17.820
And then, depending what
the bunching ratio is,

00:34:17.820 --> 00:34:21.090
this is also the time in
which you may optically

00:34:21.090 --> 00:34:23.909
pump to another ground state.

00:34:23.909 --> 00:34:26.719
So therefore, what we
have to take into account

00:34:26.719 --> 00:34:32.590
now is that we have narrower
widths in our system,

00:34:32.590 --> 00:34:38.250
and those widths correspond to
another two-level system which

00:34:38.250 --> 00:34:41.710
is driven by two photons in
which connects the two ground

00:34:41.710 --> 00:34:43.280
states.

00:34:43.280 --> 00:34:47.590
I will not give you any
derivation how this exactly

00:34:47.590 --> 00:34:50.540
leads to a lower
temperature, but I

00:34:50.540 --> 00:34:55.739
want to give you two
pictures which I have already

00:34:55.739 --> 00:34:57.400
introduced to you.

00:34:57.400 --> 00:35:03.860
One is, remember, when we
discussed Doppler cooling,

00:35:03.860 --> 00:35:07.350
the final temperature was
proportionate to gamma,

00:35:07.350 --> 00:35:09.770
the width of the transition.

00:35:09.770 --> 00:35:12.620
So now I wave my hands and
say, if you have transitions

00:35:12.620 --> 00:35:15.990
between ground states which have
a much, much smaller width--

00:35:15.990 --> 00:35:17.970
which is the rate
of optical pumping--

00:35:17.970 --> 00:35:19.820
and for low laser
power this width

00:35:19.820 --> 00:35:22.200
can become very, very narrow.

00:35:22.200 --> 00:35:24.342
But you have at
least one ingredient

00:35:24.342 --> 00:35:25.925
which can lead to a
lower temperature.

00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:34.370
OK, in all truth in
advertising, for the Sisyphus--

00:35:34.370 --> 00:35:36.780
for the polarization
gradient cooling scheme--

00:35:36.780 --> 00:35:38.530
the final temperature
is not given

00:35:38.530 --> 00:35:42.090
by gamma prime, the
rate of optical pumping.

00:35:42.090 --> 00:35:46.470
It is a proportionality factor,
but there is another factor.

00:35:46.470 --> 00:35:47.975
If you want to
learn about it, you

00:35:47.975 --> 00:35:51.410
have to read some of
the classic papers.

00:35:51.410 --> 00:35:54.240
But there is another
picture which I can also

00:35:54.240 --> 00:35:56.830
use to tell you--
and that's actually

00:35:56.830 --> 00:36:01.940
related-- why optical
pumping at least gives

00:36:01.940 --> 00:36:04.270
the possibility for
lower temperature.

00:36:04.270 --> 00:36:07.365
I explained to you with the
stimulated force in [? blue ?]

00:36:07.365 --> 00:36:11.370
molasses-- that the only
reason why we have cooling--

00:36:11.370 --> 00:36:15.010
is that the atom has a lag time.

00:36:15.010 --> 00:36:19.060
It cannot instantaneously adjust
itself to the light field.

00:36:19.060 --> 00:36:21.220
It lags behind.

00:36:21.220 --> 00:36:23.410
And you can say,
in Doppler cooling,

00:36:23.410 --> 00:36:27.260
the lag time is the
spontaneous emission time,

00:36:27.260 --> 00:36:30.870
and the inverse of it is gamma.

00:36:30.870 --> 00:36:34.110
Here, in this case,
the lag time can

00:36:34.110 --> 00:36:37.140
be the very long time
to optically pump.

00:36:37.140 --> 00:36:40.920
So therefore, if the atom is
in one hyperfine state and now

00:36:40.920 --> 00:36:45.640
moves into an area where the
polarization of the laser beams

00:36:45.640 --> 00:36:49.940
is different, it may take
a long time to adjust.

00:36:49.940 --> 00:36:54.700
And it is this lag time to
which the friction coefficient

00:36:54.700 --> 00:36:56.360
was proportional.

00:36:56.360 --> 00:37:00.350
So this is a new feature, long
delay times, narrow widths,

00:37:00.350 --> 00:37:02.780
and resonances between
ground state levels.

00:37:06.050 --> 00:37:07.940
OK, a little bit
show and tell now.

00:37:14.540 --> 00:37:15.915
Nobody thought
about polarization

00:37:15.915 --> 00:37:18.610
creating cooling, nobody
thought about Doppler cooling,

00:37:18.610 --> 00:37:21.780
but it was discovered
when people simply

00:37:21.780 --> 00:37:24.610
did Doppler molasses
and it's one

00:37:24.610 --> 00:37:27.100
of those big violations
of Murphy's law

00:37:27.100 --> 00:37:30.810
where cooling worked much better
than everybody had thought,

00:37:30.810 --> 00:37:32.920
and the result is the following.

00:37:32.920 --> 00:37:36.450
That-- when I drew for
you the blue curve, which

00:37:36.450 --> 00:37:39.220
is force versus velocity--
it's pretty much

00:37:39.220 --> 00:37:41.780
the subtraction of
two [? Lorentzian ?].

00:37:41.780 --> 00:37:45.780
What happened is-- for sodium
atoms, or for any alkali atom--

00:37:45.780 --> 00:37:48.350
it's the red curve.

00:37:48.350 --> 00:37:51.430
For large velocity you have
the Doppler cooling mechanism,

00:37:51.430 --> 00:37:57.020
but for smaller velocities you
have a steepening of the slope,

00:37:57.020 --> 00:37:59.970
and the steeper the slope,
the larger is your friction

00:37:59.970 --> 00:38:01.570
coefficient, alpha.

00:38:01.570 --> 00:38:09.550
And this is the mechanism of
polarization gradient cooling.

00:38:09.550 --> 00:38:13.220
Let me just take
this famous paper

00:38:13.220 --> 00:38:17.150
and show you one way how
polarization gradient cooling

00:38:17.150 --> 00:38:20.860
works, which is the most famous
form of sub-Doppler cooling,

00:38:20.860 --> 00:38:22.780
and this goes as follows.

00:38:22.780 --> 00:38:25.690
If you have molasses
with two laser beams

00:38:25.690 --> 00:38:28.760
and the two laser
beams are lin-perp-lin,

00:38:28.760 --> 00:38:30.900
linear polarization
perpendicular

00:38:30.900 --> 00:38:32.670
to the other linear
polarization.

00:38:32.670 --> 00:38:35.722
So you have two laser beams
with these polarization.

00:38:35.722 --> 00:38:38.870
When these two polarizations
overlap and they

00:38:38.870 --> 00:38:42.450
have the same phase, you
get light at 45 degree,

00:38:42.450 --> 00:38:45.930
but if these two polarization
have 90 degree out of phase,

00:38:45.930 --> 00:38:48.320
you get circularly
polarized light.

00:38:48.320 --> 00:38:53.040
So as these two laser
beams counter-propagate,

00:38:53.040 --> 00:38:56.710
you periodically go from
linear polarized sigma minus,

00:38:56.710 --> 00:38:58.740
linear polarized sigma plus.

00:38:58.740 --> 00:39:03.280
So you have spatial--
at any given point

00:39:03.280 --> 00:39:06.910
you have a polarization, but
the polarization changes.

00:39:06.910 --> 00:39:08.880
You have a-- you
would say, naively,

00:39:08.880 --> 00:39:13.080
lin-perp-lin don't interfere,
don't form a standing wave.

00:39:13.080 --> 00:39:16.540
Well, they do not form a
standing wave in intensity.

00:39:16.540 --> 00:39:20.850
They form a standing
wave in polarization.

00:39:20.850 --> 00:39:22.850
So now what happens
is the following.

00:39:22.850 --> 00:39:27.940
If you have a multi-level atom
and I use this simple scheme

00:39:27.940 --> 00:39:31.450
here, the different
polarizations,

00:39:31.450 --> 00:39:35.370
linear polarization
drives, the pi transition,

00:39:35.370 --> 00:39:37.170
sigma plus and sigma
minus [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:37.170 --> 00:39:39.270
different transitions,
and those transitions

00:39:39.270 --> 00:39:41.310
have different strengths.

00:39:41.310 --> 00:39:44.570
So an atom here--
when it experience

00:39:44.570 --> 00:39:46.800
this polarization--
reaches cycle,

00:39:46.800 --> 00:39:50.446
but when it experiences the
other circular polarization,

00:39:50.446 --> 00:39:54.500
it will be optically pumped
over here and then it cycles.

00:39:54.500 --> 00:39:59.250
So therefore, an atom which from
sigma plus polarization and was

00:39:59.250 --> 00:40:02.160
here, it flies over to
an area where you've

00:40:02.160 --> 00:40:06.450
sigma minus polarization, it
will actually be pumped over.

00:40:06.450 --> 00:40:09.810
So the atom will constantly
be pumped back and forth

00:40:09.810 --> 00:40:12.440
between those hyperfine states.

00:40:12.440 --> 00:40:18.770
And this actually gives rise
to a beautiful form of Sisyphus

00:40:18.770 --> 00:40:22.190
cooling that the atom
experiences sigma plus

00:40:22.190 --> 00:40:24.750
light in one ground state.

00:40:24.750 --> 00:40:29.340
It climbs up the hill, it
sees the AC Stock's shift

00:40:29.340 --> 00:40:31.740
potential-- and the AC
Stock's shift potential,

00:40:31.740 --> 00:40:36.440
because of the, for instance,
for one hyperfine state, sigma

00:40:36.440 --> 00:40:38.550
plus drives the
strongest transition--

00:40:38.550 --> 00:40:42.550
and therefore we have
sigma plus light,

00:40:42.550 --> 00:40:44.840
one ground state has
the deepest potential.

00:40:44.840 --> 00:40:47.200
Where we have sigma
minus light, it

00:40:47.200 --> 00:40:50.370
is the other ground state which
has the deepest potential.

00:40:50.370 --> 00:40:54.260
And so what happens is that the
atom is in one hyperfine state.

00:40:54.260 --> 00:40:56.550
It climbs up the
hill, and then it's

00:40:56.550 --> 00:40:58.880
optically pumped to the
other hyperfine state,

00:40:58.880 --> 00:41:05.850
and we have exactly the same
kind of Sisyphus cooling.

00:41:05.850 --> 00:41:07.980
I just show you pictures
and you sort of match it

00:41:07.980 --> 00:41:09.290
with what you know.

00:41:09.290 --> 00:41:11.520
This is more
complicated because this

00:41:11.520 --> 00:41:15.130
involves optical pumping
between hyperfine states.

00:41:15.130 --> 00:41:17.660
The different hyperfine states
have different [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:17.660 --> 00:41:19.200
coefficients and such.

00:41:19.200 --> 00:41:22.900
It's not really complicated
but more complex.

00:41:22.900 --> 00:41:25.370
What I explained to you
is how Sisyphus cooling

00:41:25.370 --> 00:41:27.950
works in the
dressed atom picture

00:41:27.950 --> 00:41:30.030
just for a two-level system.

00:41:30.030 --> 00:41:34.350
And here you find a more subtle
form of Sisyphus cooling,

00:41:34.350 --> 00:41:37.290
but this form is more
important because whenever

00:41:37.290 --> 00:41:40.500
you operate a
magneto-optic trap,

00:41:40.500 --> 00:41:42.610
you get this cooling
mechanism for free.

00:41:49.360 --> 00:41:58.030
OK, so that's all I want to tell
you about sub-Doppler cooling.

00:41:58.030 --> 00:42:02.210
OK, sub-recoil cooling, we
can quickly deal with it

00:42:02.210 --> 00:42:06.300
because I want to prove to you
here that sub-recoil cooling is

00:42:06.300 --> 00:42:08.100
impossible.

00:42:08.100 --> 00:42:10.730
And unless you tell me what
this wrong in my derivation,

00:42:10.730 --> 00:42:12.480
I don't need to discuss
sub-recoil cooling

00:42:12.480 --> 00:42:14.760
because I've convinced
you that it's impossible .

00:42:14.760 --> 00:42:19.010
OK, so let's assume our atom
has an initial kinetic energy

00:42:19.010 --> 00:42:21.910
and then we absorb one photon.

00:42:21.910 --> 00:42:25.560
That would mean the momentum has
now changed by the laser photon

00:42:25.560 --> 00:42:29.710
by the recoil-- and
then it emits a photon,

00:42:29.710 --> 00:42:33.420
so the momentum gets reduced
by the immediate photon--

00:42:33.420 --> 00:42:36.740
and all I do is I ask,
what is the difference

00:42:36.740 --> 00:42:39.560
between the initial
kinetic energy

00:42:39.560 --> 00:42:44.530
and the final kinetic energy
after two photons-- a laser

00:42:44.530 --> 00:42:49.100
photon and the spontaneously
photon-- have been exchanged?

00:42:49.100 --> 00:42:51.590
And what you find is--
and this is just exact--

00:42:51.590 --> 00:42:55.625
that the change in energy is
two times the recoil energy.

00:42:55.625 --> 00:43:01.860
The recoil energy is h-bar
square K square over 2m, plus--

00:43:01.860 --> 00:43:07.300
and this is now the
cross-term-- plus KL--

00:43:07.300 --> 00:43:11.510
the K vector of the laser--
minus K spontaneous emission

00:43:11.510 --> 00:43:13.590
times the velocity.

00:43:13.590 --> 00:43:16.690
And now, of course, we
assume-- which is correct--

00:43:16.690 --> 00:43:20.220
that spontaneous emission goes
randomly in all directions.

00:43:20.220 --> 00:43:22.670
Therefore, if we average
over many cycles,

00:43:22.670 --> 00:43:25.040
this does not contribute.

00:43:25.040 --> 00:43:29.660
So therefore we find now that
the average energy exchanged

00:43:29.660 --> 00:43:33.750
by an absorption and
emission event is two times

00:43:33.750 --> 00:43:41.840
the recoil energy plus h-bar
K laser times [? width ?],

00:43:41.840 --> 00:43:45.770
and we want to make it negative
because we want to cool.

00:43:45.770 --> 00:43:49.300
Well, we make it negative by
arranging the laser beam--

00:43:49.300 --> 00:43:51.700
surprise, surprise--
counter-propagating

00:43:51.700 --> 00:43:52.800
to the velocity.

00:43:52.800 --> 00:43:55.640
This is how we can
get the best cooling.

00:43:55.640 --> 00:43:58.290
Well, surprise, that's
what we expected.

00:43:58.290 --> 00:44:08.080
But you find, of course, that
when this velocity is a very

00:44:08.080 --> 00:44:15.480
small then K V is
smaller than K squared.

00:44:15.480 --> 00:44:20.200
So therefore, once the velocity
is smaller than the recoil

00:44:20.200 --> 00:44:26.410
velocity of a single
photon, you cannot choose--

00:44:26.410 --> 00:44:32.830
you cannot make this equation
or this expression go negative.

00:44:32.830 --> 00:44:34.600
In other words, what
I've shown to you

00:44:34.600 --> 00:44:38.920
is if there is an atom which
has a velocity which is smaller

00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:44.315
than the recoil velocity
of a photon, whenever

00:44:44.315 --> 00:44:48.550
this atom scatters
a single photon,

00:44:48.550 --> 00:44:52.300
it will be hotter
than it was before.

00:44:55.902 --> 00:44:57.860
So is it clear, what I've
shown you, in energy?

00:44:57.860 --> 00:45:00.080
When an atom has
a velocity which

00:45:00.080 --> 00:45:03.040
is smaller than the
recoil velocity,

00:45:03.040 --> 00:45:07.340
any further photon
scattering will not cool.

00:45:07.340 --> 00:45:09.460
It will lead to an
energy transfer delta

00:45:09.460 --> 00:45:12.440
E, which is large,
which is possible.

00:45:16.530 --> 00:45:21.907
So that shows you that
sub-recoil cooling

00:45:21.907 --> 00:45:22.490
is impossible.

00:45:30.220 --> 00:45:32.160
Any idea how we can
sub-recoil cool?

